ntent-id="fn0066" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0066" class="end-note-link">66</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">On the autonomy of EU law to determine the internal effects of international law, <em>see</em> Case C-160/09, Katsivardas—Nikolaos Tsitsikas v. Ipourgos Ikonomikon 2010 E.C.R. I-4591, ¶ 32.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0067" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0067" class="end-note-link">67</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Joined Cases C-120/06 P and C-121/06 P, FIAMM v. Council, 2008 E.C.R. I-6513, ¶¶ 97–99; Case C-366/10, Air Transport Ass’n of America, paras 110–111.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0068" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0068" class="end-note-link">68</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Opinion 1/09, 2011 E.C.R. I-1137.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0069" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0069" class="end-note-link">69</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Joined Cases C-402/05P &amp; 415/05P Kadi, 2008 E.C.R. I-6351.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0070" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0070" class="end-note-link">70</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Case 43/75, Sabena (No. 2), 1976 E.C.R. 455, ¶ 33.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0071" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0071" class="end-note-link">71</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Case 41/74, Van Duyn v. Home Office, 1974 E.C.R. 1337, ¶ 12.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0072" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0072" class="end-note-link">72</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Joined Cases C-6/90 &amp; C-9/90, Francovich v. Italy, 1991 E.C.R. I-5357, ¶¶ 33–34.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0073" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0073" class="end-note-link">73</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Case C-224/01, Köbler v. Austria, 2003 E.C.R. I-239, ¶ 33.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0074" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0074" class="end-note-link">74</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Case C-194/94, CIA Security v. Signalson, 1996 E.C.R. I-2201, ¶ 48.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0075" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0075" class="end-note-link">75</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Case 43/75, Sabena (No. 2), 1976 E.C.R. 455, ¶ 19.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0076" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0076" class="end-note-link">76</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Case C-194/94, CIA Security, 1996 E.C.R. I-2201, ¶ 48.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0077" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0077" class="end-note-link">77</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><em>See</em>, respectively, Case 152/84, Marshall v. Southampton and SW Hampshire Area Health Authority, 1986 E.C.R. 723; Joined Cases C-46 &amp; 48, Brasserie du Pêcheur v. Germany and R. v. Secretary of State for Transport, <em>ex parte</em> Factortame (No. 3), 1996 E.C.R. I-1029.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0078" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0078" class="end-note-link">78</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">These must be no less favorable than for equivalent domestic actions and not render exercise of the right excessively difficult or practically impossible, Case C-432/05, Unibet v. Justitiekanslern, 2007 E.C.R. I-2271.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0079" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0079" class="end-note-link">79</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><span class="small-caps">Damian Chalmers, Gareth Davies &amp; Giorgio Monti, European Union Law</span> 223–227 (2d ed. 2010).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0080" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0080" class="end-note-link">80</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><em>See, e.g.</em>, Case C-106/89, Marleasing v. La Comercial, 1990 E.C.R. I-4135.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0081" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0081" class="end-note-link">81</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><span class="small-caps">Michael Oakeshott, The Vocabulary of a Modern European State</span> 245–266 (Luke O’Sullivan ed., 2008).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0082" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0082" class="end-note-link">82</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><span class="small-caps">Martin Loughlin, The Foundations of Public Law</span> 185–186 (2010).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0083" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0083" class="end-note-link">83</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><span class="small-caps">Bill Davies, Resisting the European Court of Justice: West Germany’s Confrontation with European Law, 1949–1979</span>, at 55–56 (2012).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0084" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0084" class="end-note-link">84</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">There is no study prior to this of the background of litigants invoking EU law. On studies of different provisions, <em>see</em> Damian Chalmers, <em>The Positioning of EU Judicial Politics within the United Kingdom</em>, 23W. <span class="small-caps">Eur. Pol</span>. 169 (2000); B. Bepuly, <em>The Application of EC Law in Austria</em>, IWE Working Paper No. 39, <a class="link link-uri" href="http://www.iwe.oeaw.ac.at">http://www.iwe.oeaw.ac.at</a>; Francisco Ramos Romeu, <em>Law and Politics in the Application of EC Law: Spanish Courts and the European Court of Justice 1986–2000</em>, 43 <span class="small-caps">Common Mkt L. Rev.</span> 395 (2006).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0085" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0085" class="end-note-link">85</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">European Commission, 29th Annual Report on Monitoring the Application of EU Law 2011, COM(2012)714, 2.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0086" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0086" class="end-note-link">86</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">The dominant instruments are, respectively, Directive 77/388/EEC on the harmonization of the laws of the Member States relating to turnover taxes, 1977 O.J. L 145/1 [hereinafter “Sixth VAT Directive”]; Regulation 1408/71 on the application of social security schemes to employed persons, to self-employed persons and to members of their families moving within the Community, as amended and updated by Regulation 118/97, 1997 O.J. L 28/1, as amended by Regulation 1992/2006, 2006 O.J. L 392/1; Regulation 2658/87 on the tariff and statistical nomenclature and on the Common Customs Tariff, 1987 O.J. L 256/1; Regulation 2913/92 establishing the Community Customs Code, 1992 O.J. L 302/1, as amended by Regulation 2700/2000, 2000 O.J. L 311/17; Framework Decision 2001/220/JHA on the standing of victims in criminal proceedings, 2001 O.J. L 82/1; Framework Decision 2002/584/JHA on the European arrest warrant and the surrender procedures between Member States, 2002 O.J. L 190/1.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0087" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0087" class="end-note-link">87</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">European Commission, Making the Single Market Deliver; Annual Governance Check Up 2011, at 9 (2011).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0088" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0088" class="end-note-link">88</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Damian Chalmers &amp; Mariana Chaves, <em>The Reference Points of EU Judicial Politics</em>, 19 <span class="small-caps">J. Eur. Pub. Pol’y</span> 25, 31–32 (2012).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0089" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0089" class="end-note-link">89</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">As all litigation involves two parties and it is rare that one arm of the state litigates against the other, a figure of 50% would represent the state being a party in nearly all the litigation.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0090" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0090" class="end-note-link">90</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">This figure under-represents the number of organizations who are litigants as a number of cases formally brought by individuals are supported and organized by these. <em>See, e.g.</em>, Alec Stone Sweet &amp; Kathleen Stranz, <em>Rights Adjudication and Constitutional Pluralism in Germany and Europe</em>, 19 <span class="small-caps">J. Eur. Pub. Pol’y</span> 92 (2012).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0091" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0091" class="end-note-link">91</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">A good description is provided in Case C-285/11, Bonik, Judgment of Dec. 6, 2012.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0092" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0092" class="end-note-link">92</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility"><em>See</em>, respectively, Case C-416/10 Križan, Judgment of January 15, 2013; Case C-420/11, Leth, Judgment of March 14, 2013.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0093" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0093" class="end-note-link">93</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">A strong salience was taken to be where 45 percent or more of the judgments were cited by the Court in its Annual Reports.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0094" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0094" class="end-note-link">94</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">In addition to patrol norms and thickly evaluative norms, a third narrative is emerging, which is litigation of property rights, notably intellectual property rights. Legislation has only proliferated on this in recent years.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0095" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0095" class="end-note-link">95</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Chalmers &amp; Chaves, <em>supra</em> note 88, at 32–34.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0096" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0096" class="end-note-link">96</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">European Commission, Towards a Single Market Act, COM(2010)608, Proposal No. 30; European Commission, Non-Discrimination and Equal Opportunities for All—A Framework Strategy, COM(2005)224; European Commission, Strategy for Equality Between Women and Men 2010–2015, COM(2010)491.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0097" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0097" class="end-note-link">97</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Czech Constitutional Court, Pl ÚS 5/12, Slovak Pensions, Judgment of Jan. 31, 2012 (Czech).</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0098" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span class="label fn-label"><span rel="nofollow" data-fn-id="fn0098" class="end-note-link">98</span></span><div class="footnote-content"><p class="footnote-compatibility">Attorney General of Cyprus v. Konstantinou [2007] 3 C.M.L.R. 24.</p></div></span></div><div content-id="fn0099" class="footnote"><span class="fn"><span c